<h2>Ship Buying Guide</h2>

<div class="subSectionTitle">Intro</div>
<div class="subSectionDesc">Hello, and welcome to "The Ship Buyer's Guide"! You will learn what ships there are, all of the Pros and Cons of each, and which one suits your playing style! This guide should be accurate for the first 3 or 4 galaxy systems.<div style="clear: both"></div></div>
<br>
<div class="subSectionTitle">Section I : Fighters</div>
<div class="subSectionDesc">Fighters are a basic, staple ship. They are known for High Maneuverability and Damage, making them good starter ships. However, they usually lack Storage Slots, but can offer them for a higher price. There are 4 types of fighters you will see throughout your galactic travels.<div style="clear: both"></div></div>
<br>
<br>
<img src="https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/913533862982112184/D3962A0D51539BC461DE3F7A6066C397BC7D3372/" class="responsive">
<div class="subSectionDesc">This type is what I like to call "The Dolphin". They have a sleek, modern design, with a cockpit reminiscent of the one of the Starter Ship. Usually found in shades of blue, or teal. They are a Medium-High level ship, with more than average Storage Slots and Damage Boost. They can be found for around $2,000,000 for a class C, and average 18-22 Storage Slots. <div style="clear: both"></div></div>
<br>
<img src="https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/913533862982112007/594E560E74A07B7E4B2B8E8DADB8EFA1ADD4E1DE/" class="responsive">
<div class="subSectionDesc"> I call this ship type "Jetstream" because it showcases it's large turbine that basically makes up almost all of it's body. They are usually found in Dark Blue or Bright Red. They have high Damage Boosts in class B, but have, on average, less maneuverability than other fighters. They have an average of about 18-20 Storage Slots. These are great fighters, but are more than decent in other ways. Average cost: $1,700,000.<div style="clear: both"></div></div>
<br>
<br>
<img src="https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/913533862982407470/61D5AC0C4750FA5ED94C95B549DCF8A3333B7FCD/" class="responsive">
<div class="subSectionDesc">I named this ship type "The Original". This type is almost exactly the same as the original given fighter. This one in particular was around $4,000,000 I think. It, however, was class A with 22 slots.They are very rarely seen, and I would say, not worth it. You could buy a class B of any other fighter and get just as much out of it for half the price.<div style="clear: both"></div></div>
<br>
<img src="https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/913533862982407266/90EF45A018FED0C2EC8EF5360D23320818387F1F/" class="responsive">
<div class="subSectionDesc"> This type of ship I nicknamed the "Mosquito" for obvious reasons. If you couldn't tell, its most distinctive feature is it's long pointy nose, looking like the piecing beak of a mosquito. They have relatively high speeds with medium damage. They have about 16-20 Storage Slots at class C, Making them fast, lightweight fighters. They fit the class pretty good, and an average of $1,700,000<div style="clear: both"></div></div>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<div class="subSectionTitle">Section II: Shuttles</div>

<div class="subSectionDesc">Blunt and blocky, these ships aren't very appealing to the eye, a dealbreaker for most consumers. But if you can look past their shapes and Trademark rectangular cockpit window, you can see why these ships are very appealing.<div style="clear: both"></div></div>

<img src="https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/913533862982407369/A7B79BA46B5FD1D90CF966DF57DFEA055EE452A5/" class="responsive">
<div class="subSectionDesc">Although they have very different looks, they all are relatively the same. Here are the reasons why one of these is worth its money:<div style="clear: both"></div></div>
<br>
<br>
<img src="https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/913533862982407586/52D86D0437F379773AD7509FB1D13613568725B6/" class="responsive">
<div class="subSectionDesc">WIP<div style="clear: both"></div></div>
<br>
<br>
